{"parentUuid":"5b48b1ca-a72e-452d-902a-ea7c59008f53","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ac8f883e15ef792f8","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01NVx2qVy3CeBtMWzUpyxH4p","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01GnwgLBt8rm79sH63CrybsE","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"self-improvement AI requires verifiable reward ground truth evaluator no signal"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1003,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6052,"cache_read_input_tokens":6425,"output_tokens":320,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6052},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1003,"output_tokens":320,"cache_read_input_tokens":6425,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6052,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6052,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":8359}}},"requestId":"req_011CcG26Rasr9FmZr4wvDvw3","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"04adf0ca-2c7b-4b12-a7e0-51943edcd195","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:22.335Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"5b48b1ca-a72e-452d-902a-ea7c59008f53","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"ac8f883e15ef792f8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0197qtqitZYwcym9rFqUJTNC","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Self-Taught Optimizer STOP Zelikman utility function scaffolding improvement\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation\",\"url\":\"https://blog.athina.ai/self-taught-optimizer-stop-recursively-self-improving-code-generation\"},{\"title\":\"[2310.02304] Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation\",\"url\":\"https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2310.02304\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - microsoft/stop: Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/microsoft/stop\"},{\"title\":\"Enhancing AI Systems via Self-Improving Scaffolding\",\"url\":\"https://hub.athina.ai/research-papers/self-taught-optimizer-stop-recursively-self-improving-code-generation/\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation - Microsoft Research\",\"url\":\"https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/publication/self-taught-optimizer-stop-recursively-self-improving-code-generation/\"},{\"title\":\"[2310.02304] Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.02304\"},{\"title\":\"[PDF] Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation | Semantic Scholar\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Self-Taught-Optimizer-(STOP):-Recursively-Code-Zelikman-Lorch/3fe940a1f121f083cb90c568fc6fa2951bb27dda\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving ...\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/pdf?id=46Zgqo4QIU\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2310.02304\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP) and the related concepts:\n\n## Overview\n\nEric Zelikman and his team introduced STOP, a system that uses a language model to iteratively enhance itself, showing promising results in improving performance across different tasks.\n\n## How It Works\n\nSeveral recent advances in AI systems (e.g., Tree-of-Thoughts and Program-Aided Language Models) solve problems by providing a \"scaffolding\" program that structures multiple calls to language models to generate better outputs. A scaffolding program is written in a programming language such as Python. In this work, we use a language-model-infused scaffolding program to improve itself.\n\nThe core mechanism involves: A seed \"improver\" that improves an input program according to a given utility function by querying a language model several times and returning the best solution. This seed improver is then run to improve itself.\n\n## Key Results\n\nAcross a small set of downstream tasks, the resulting improved improver generates programs with significantly better performance than its seed improver.\n\n## Self-Improvement Strategies\n\nSTOP uses strategies like beam search, genetic algorithms, and simulated annealing, all directed by the language model's suggestions.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"9756b75e-199c-48e1-95e0-547a64ced2d7","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:29.621Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Self-Taught Optimizer STOP Zelikman utility function scaffolding improvement","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01ETmz664j3ucJ2Fn5L4QWn5","content":[{"title":"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation","url":"https://blog.athina.ai/self-taught-optimizer-stop-recursively-self-improving-code-generation"},{"title":"[2310.02304] Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation","url":"https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2310.02304"},{"title":"GitHub - microsoft/stop: Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/microsoft/stop"},{"title":"Enhancing AI Systems via Self-Improving Scaffolding","url":"https://hub.athina.ai/research-papers/self-taught-optimizer-stop-recursively-self-improving-code-generation/"},{"title":"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation - Microsoft Research","url":"https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/publication/self-taught-optimizer-stop-recursively-self-improving-code-generation/"},{"title":"[2310.02304] Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.02304"},{"title":"[PDF] Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation | Semantic Scholar","url":"https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Self-Taught-Optimizer-(STOP):-Recursively-Code-Zelikman-Lorch/3fe940a1f121f083cb90c568fc6fa2951bb27dda"},{"title":"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving ...","url":"https://openreview.net/pdf?id=46Zgqo4QIU"},{"title":"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2310.02304"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP) and the related concepts:\n\n## Overview\n\nEric Zelikman and his team introduced STOP, a system that uses a language model to iteratively enhance itself, showing promising results in improving performance across different tasks.\n\n## How It Works\n\nSeveral recent advances in AI systems (e.g., Tree-of-Thoughts and Program-Aided Language Models) solve problems by providing a \"scaffolding\" program that structures multiple calls to language models to generate better outputs. A scaffolding program is written in a programming language such as Python. In this work, we use a language-model-infused scaffolding program to improve itself.\n\nThe core mechanism involves: A seed \"improver\" that improves an input program according to a given utility function by querying a language model several times and returning the best solution. This seed improver is then run to improve itself.\n\n## Key Results\n\nAcross a small set of downstream tasks, the resulting improved improver generates programs with significantly better performance than its seed improver.\n\n## Self-Improvement Strategies\n\nSTOP uses strategies like beam search, genetic algorithms, and simulated annealing, all directed by the language model's suggestions."],"durationSeconds":7.158498749999329,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"5b48b1ca-a72e-452d-902a-ea7c59008f53","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"59e44e6d-de07-4afc-a6cb-c103629fb014","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"ac8f883e15ef792f8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019MeMyG2PXuGE6tth617kR9","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"AlphaEvolve automated evaluation function machine-gradeable problems DeepMind\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Google DeepMind's AlphaEvolve: A Breakthrough in AI-Driven Scientific Discovery\",\"url\":\"https://theoutpost.ai/news-story/google-deep-mind-s-alpha-evolve-a-breakthrough-in-ai-driven-algorithm-discovery-15378/\"},{\"title\":\"Google's DeepMind Unveils AlphaEvolve, an AI System that Designs and Optimizes Algorithms\",\"url\":\"https://www.maginative.com/article/googles-deepmind-unveils-alphaevolve-an-ai-system-that-designs-and-optimizes-algorithms/\"},{\"title\":\"DeepMind's general scientific entity AlphaEvolve surpasses mathematical limits in collaboration with Tao Zhe Xian-bincial\",\"url\":\"https://www.bincial.com/news/tzArtificialIntelligence/173665\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\",\"url\":\"https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"DeepMind's AlphaEvolve Surpasses Expectations in Solving Math and Science Problems | AI News\",\"url\":\"https://opentools.ai/news/deepminds-alphaevolve-surpasses-expectations-in-solving-math-and-science-problems\"},{\"title\":\"Google’s AlphaEvolve: The AI agent that reclaimed 0.7% of Google’s compute – and how to copy it | VentureBeat\",\"url\":\"https://venturebeat.com/infrastructure/googles-alphaevolve-the-ai-agent-that-reclaimed-0-7-of-googles-compute-and-how-to-copy-it\"},{\"title\":\"DeepMind's AlphaGo to AlphaEvolve: The Thinking Game & The Alpha Models Redesigning Their Own World - Tabula Rasa To Recursive AI\",\"url\":\"https://interestingengineering.substack.com/p/deepminds-alphago-to-alphaevolve\"},{\"title\":\"The Dawn of Algorithmic Evolution: AlphaEvolve and Its Transformative Impact | doing the math for you\",\"url\":\"https://gpt.gekko.de/alphaevolve-impact-science-economy-society/\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind\",\"url\":\"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\"},{\"title\":\"DeepMind claims its newest AI tool is a whiz at math and science problems | TechCrunch\",\"url\":\"https://techcrunch.com/2025/05/14/deepmind-claims-its-newest-ai-tool-is-a-whiz-at-math-and-science-problems/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about AlphaEvolve:\n\n## Overview\n\nDeepMind has developed AlphaEvolve, a new AI system to tackle problems with \"machine-gradeable\" solutions. AlphaEvolve combines the power of large language models (LLMs) with evolutionary algorithms to tackle complex problems across various scientific domains.\n\n## How It Works\n\nAlphaEvolve takes a user-defined program and evaluation function, then iteratively mutates, scores, and evolves it using an ensemble of Gemini Pro and Gemini Flash models. Every iteration proposed by the pair of LLMs is accepted or rejected based on a user-supplied \"evaluate\" function that returns machine-gradable metrics.\n\n## Key Feature: Automated Evaluation\n\nAlphaEvolve uses LLMs to generate answers to prompts, and automatically evaluates and scores these answers for accuracy. As AlphaEvolve deals with machine-gradeable problems, users must provide a mechanism for automatically evaluating generated solutions, commonly done by mapping solutions to a set of scalar evaluation metrics.\n\n## Applications and Results\n\nIn internal tests, AlphaEvolve improved the state of the art on 14 matrix multiplication benchmarks, including a long-standing open problem from 1969, and made advances in over 20% of the 50+ open mathematical problems it was tested on. It's already in use optimizing Google's AI infrastructure, chips, and scheduling systems.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"c3da3bbf-14b5-40b5-9490-dba116a542d6","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:29.775Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"AlphaEvolve automated evaluation function machine-gradeable problems DeepMind","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01HoJUaTvSxReWpHe9yqxjt8","content":[{"title":"Google DeepMind's AlphaEvolve: A Breakthrough in AI-Driven Scientific Discovery","url":"https://theoutpost.ai/news-story/google-deep-mind-s-alpha-evolve-a-breakthrough-in-ai-driven-algorithm-discovery-15378/"},{"title":"Google's DeepMind Unveils AlphaEvolve, an AI System that Designs and Optimizes Algorithms","url":"https://www.maginative.com/article/googles-deepmind-unveils-alphaevolve-an-ai-system-that-designs-and-optimizes-algorithms/"},{"title":"DeepMind's general scientific entity AlphaEvolve surpasses mathematical limits in collaboration with Tao Zhe Xian-bincial","url":"https://www.bincial.com/news/tzArtificialIntelligence/173665"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery","url":"https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf"},{"title":"DeepMind's AlphaEvolve Surpasses Expectations in Solving Math and Science Problems | AI News","url":"https://opentools.ai/news/deepminds-alphaevolve-surpasses-expectations-in-solving-math-and-science-problems"},{"title":"Google’s AlphaEvolve: The AI agent that reclaimed 0.7% of Google’s compute – and how to copy it | VentureBeat","url":"https://venturebeat.com/infrastructure/googles-alphaevolve-the-ai-agent-that-reclaimed-0-7-of-googles-compute-and-how-to-copy-it"},{"title":"DeepMind's AlphaGo to AlphaEvolve: The Thinking Game & The Alpha Models Redesigning Their Own World - Tabula Rasa To Recursive AI","url":"https://interestingengineering.substack.com/p/deepminds-alphago-to-alphaevolve"},{"title":"The Dawn of Algorithmic Evolution: AlphaEvolve and Its Transformative Impact | doing the math for you","url":"https://gpt.gekko.de/alphaevolve-impact-science-economy-society/"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind","url":"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/"},{"title":"DeepMind claims its newest AI tool is a whiz at math and science problems | TechCrunch","url":"https://techcrunch.com/2025/05/14/deepmind-claims-its-newest-ai-tool-is-a-whiz-at-math-and-science-problems/"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about AlphaEvolve:\n\n## Overview\n\nDeepMind has developed AlphaEvolve, a new AI system to tackle problems with \"machine-gradeable\" solutions. AlphaEvolve combines the power of large language models (LLMs) with evolutionary algorithms to tackle complex problems across various scientific domains.\n\n## How It Works\n\nAlphaEvolve takes a user-defined program and evaluation function, then iteratively mutates, scores, and evolves it using an ensemble of Gemini Pro and Gemini Flash models. Every iteration proposed by the pair of LLMs is accepted or rejected based on a user-supplied \"evaluate\" function that returns machine-gradable metrics.\n\n## Key Feature: Automated Evaluation\n\nAlphaEvolve uses LLMs to generate answers to prompts, and automatically evaluates and scores these answers for accuracy. As AlphaEvolve deals with machine-gradeable problems, users must provide a mechanism for automatically evaluating generated solutions, commonly done by mapping solutions to a set of scalar evaluation metrics.\n\n## Applications and Results\n\nIn internal tests, AlphaEvolve improved the state of the art on 14 matrix multiplication benchmarks, including a long-standing open problem from 1969, and made advances in over 20% of the 50+ open mathematical problems it was tested on. It's already in use optimizing Google's AI infrastructure, chips, and scheduling systems."],"durationSeconds":9.185219542000443,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"59e44e6d-de07-4afc-a6cb-c103629fb014","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"c28c852f-9358-4d90-895c-d51508a560e5","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"ac8f883e15ef792f8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01ML1egdZt1pRFfXEHBnxbb9","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Darwin Godel Machine self-improving SWE-bench Polyglot coding benchmark Sakana Clune\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"The Darwin Gödel Machine: AI that improves itself by rewriting its own code\",\"url\":\"https://sakana.ai/dgm/\"},{\"title\":\"[2505.22954] Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.22954\"},{\"title\":\"Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents | OpenReview\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/forum?id=pUpzQZTvGY\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/392204438_Darwin_Godel_Machine_Open-Ended_Evolution_of_Self-Improving_Agents\"},{\"title\":\"Paper page - Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/papers/2505.22954\"},{\"title\":\"Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.22954\"},{\"title\":\"Darwin Gödel Machine - by Grigory Sapunov - Gonzo ML\",\"url\":\"https://gonzoml.substack.com/p/darwin-godel-machine\"},{\"title\":\"AI That Can Improve Itself | Richard Cornelius Suwandi\",\"url\":\"https://richardcsuwandi.github.io/blog/2025/dgm/\"},{\"title\":\"The Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Improvement via Recursive Code Mutation and Empirical Fitness | by Adnan Masood, PhD. | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@adnanmasood/the-darwin-g%C3%B6del-machine-open-ended-improvement-via-recursive-code-mutation-and-empirical-fitness-a777681d73e4\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - jennyzzt/dgm: Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/jennyzzt/dgm\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about the Darwin Gödel Machine and the related concepts you asked about:\n\n## Darwin Gödel Machine Overview\n\nThe Darwin Gödel Machine can continuously self-improve by modifying its own codebase. The Gödel machine is a theoretical system that repeatedly modifies itself in a provably beneficial manner.\n\n## Performance on Benchmarks\n\nSWE-bench is a widely used benchmark requiring agents to resolve real-world GitHub issues, and Polyglot is a multi-language coding benchmark. \n\nThe system achieved remarkable improvements on both benchmarks:\n- On SWE-bench, the DGM automatically improved its performance from 20.0% to 50.0%.\n- On Polyglot, the DGM jumped performance from an initial 14.2% to 30.7%, which far surpasses the representative hand-designed agent by Aider.\n\n## Self-Improvement Mechanisms\n\nThe DGM's ability to modify its own code speeds up its own learning, and a control without self-improvement performs far worse. A DGM variant whose self-improvement process was exclusively guided by its performance on Python tasks within the Polyglot benchmark subsequently demonstrated significant performance gains on tasks in entirely different programming languages (like Rust, C++, and Go).\n\n## Research Details\n\nThe work was conducted by researchers at Sakana and other institutions. The DGM automatically improves its coding capabilities (e.g., better code editing tools, long-context window management, peer-review mechanisms). All code is open-sourced at https://github.com/jennyzzt/dgm.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"b312d260-4b98-4a6b-8f70-dc346a667f50","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:32.168Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Darwin Godel Machine self-improving SWE-bench Polyglot coding benchmark Sakana Clune","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_012JFLi8SuHLLcgXycyB2dCr","content":[{"title":"The Darwin Gödel Machine: AI that improves itself by rewriting its own code","url":"https://sakana.ai/dgm/"},{"title":"[2505.22954] Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.22954"},{"title":"Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents | OpenReview","url":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=pUpzQZTvGY"},{"title":"(PDF) Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/392204438_Darwin_Godel_Machine_Open-Ended_Evolution_of_Self-Improving_Agents"},{"title":"Paper page - Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents","url":"https://huggingface.co/papers/2505.22954"},{"title":"Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.22954"},{"title":"Darwin Gödel Machine - by Grigory Sapunov - Gonzo ML","url":"https://gonzoml.substack.com/p/darwin-godel-machine"},{"title":"AI That Can Improve Itself | Richard Cornelius Suwandi","url":"https://richardcsuwandi.github.io/blog/2025/dgm/"},{"title":"The Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Improvement via Recursive Code Mutation and Empirical Fitness | by Adnan Masood, PhD. | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@adnanmasood/the-darwin-g%C3%B6del-machine-open-ended-improvement-via-recursive-code-mutation-and-empirical-fitness-a777681d73e4"},{"title":"GitHub - jennyzzt/dgm: Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/jennyzzt/dgm"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about the Darwin Gödel Machine and the related concepts you asked about:\n\n## Darwin Gödel Machine Overview\n\nThe Darwin Gödel Machine can continuously self-improve by modifying its own codebase. The Gödel machine is a theoretical system that repeatedly modifies itself in a provably beneficial manner.\n\n## Performance on Benchmarks\n\nSWE-bench is a widely used benchmark requiring agents to resolve real-world GitHub issues, and Polyglot is a multi-language coding benchmark. \n\nThe system achieved remarkable improvements on both benchmarks:\n- On SWE-bench, the DGM automatically improved its performance from 20.0% to 50.0%.\n- On Polyglot, the DGM jumped performance from an initial 14.2% to 30.7%, which far surpasses the representative hand-designed agent by Aider.\n\n## Self-Improvement Mechanisms\n\nThe DGM's ability to modify its own code speeds up its own learning, and a control without self-improvement performs far worse. A DGM variant whose self-improvement process was exclusively guided by its performance on Python tasks within the Polyglot benchmark subsequently demonstrated significant performance gains on tasks in entirely different programming languages (like Rust, C++, and Go).\n\n## Research Details\n\nThe work was conducted by researchers at Sakana and other institutions. The DGM automatically improves its coding capabilities (e.g., better code editing tools, long-context window management, peer-review mechanisms). All code is open-sourced at https://github.com/jennyzzt/dgm."],"durationSeconds":10.206080000000075,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c28c852f-9358-4d90-895c-d51508a560e5","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"04adf0ca-2c7b-4b12-a7e0-51943edcd195","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"ac8f883e15ef792f8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GnwgLBt8rm79sH63CrybsE","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"self-improvement AI requires verifiable reward ground truth evaluator no signal\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Audited Skill-Graph Self-Improvement for Agentic LLMs via Verifiable Rewards, Experience Synthesis, and Continual Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.23760\"},{\"title\":\"What are Verifiable Rewards? | AI21\",\"url\":\"https://www.ai21.com/glossary/foundational-llm/what-are-verifiable-rewards/\"},{\"title\":\"RLSR: Reinforcement Learning from Self Reward\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.08827\"},{\"title\":\"Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards: Unlocking reliable AI reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://toloka.ai/blog/reinforcement-learning-with-verifiable-rewards-unlocking-reliable-ai-reasoning/\"},{\"title\":\"Self Rewarding Self Improving\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.08827v1\"},{\"title\":\"Trust, But Verify: A Self-Verification Approach to Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.13445\"},{\"title\":\"Agent Self-Correction: From Reflexion to Process Reward Models | Zylos Research\",\"url\":\"https://zylos.ai/research/2026-05-12-agent-self-correction-reflexion-to-prm\"},{\"title\":\"RLVR: Verifiable Rewards for Reliable Enterprise LLMs | Appen\",\"url\":\"https://www.appen.com/blog/rlvr\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found regarding self-improvement AI, verifiable rewards, and ground truth evaluators:\n\n## Verifiable Rewards and Ground Truth\n\nVerifiable rewards are a class of reward signals used in reinforcement learning for LLMs where the correctness of a model's output can be confirmed objectively against a known ground truth. Unlike preference-based rewards which rely on human raters or a trained reward model, verifiable rewards can be checked automatically and unambiguously, making them a highly reliable and scalable source of training signal for tasks that have definite right answers.\n\n## Self-Improvement Without Ground Truth\n\nInterestingly, recent research explores self-improvement even when ground truth isn't available. One novel approach enables models to self-improve through self-judging by leveraging the generator-verifier gap, investigating whether models can provide reliable reward signals without access to ground truth answers. Researchers demonstrated that LLMs functioning as judges provide stable reward signals, establishing a complete self-improvement loop without requiring external verification by implementing a system where models generate their own practice problems, solve them, and then evaluate the correctness of their solutions.\n\n## Verifier Requirements\n\nVerifiable reward construction uses decomposed rewards designed to be reconstructible from evidence bundles, with components that score tool validity, task success using deterministic evaluators when available, and skill reuse.\n\nThe key tension in your query—the need for ground truth when no signal exists—is being addressed through self-judging approaches that leverage the asymmetry between generating and verifying solutions.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"995089e1-cc13-4613-bf92-a0662eaaa90f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:37.068Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"self-improvement AI requires verifiable reward ground truth evaluator no signal","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01RkZb3PA83KJxyxrRTeQfQw","content":[{"title":"Audited Skill-Graph Self-Improvement for Agentic LLMs via Verifiable Rewards, Experience Synthesis, and Continual Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.23760"},{"title":"What are Verifiable Rewards? | AI21","url":"https://www.ai21.com/glossary/foundational-llm/what-are-verifiable-rewards/"},{"title":"RLSR: Reinforcement Learning from Self Reward","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.08827"},{"title":"Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards: Unlocking reliable AI reasoning","url":"https://toloka.ai/blog/reinforcement-learning-with-verifiable-rewards-unlocking-reliable-ai-reasoning/"},{"title":"Self Rewarding Self Improving","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.08827v1"},{"title":"Trust, But Verify: A Self-Verification Approach to Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.13445"},{"title":"Agent Self-Correction: From Reflexion to Process Reward Models | Zylos Research","url":"https://zylos.ai/research/2026-05-12-agent-self-correction-reflexion-to-prm"},{"title":"RLVR: Verifiable Rewards for Reliable Enterprise LLMs | Appen","url":"https://www.appen.com/blog/rlvr"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding self-improvement AI, verifiable rewards, and ground truth evaluators:\n\n## Verifiable Rewards and Ground Truth\n\nVerifiable rewards are a class of reward signals used in reinforcement learning for LLMs where the correctness of a model's output can be confirmed objectively against a known ground truth. Unlike preference-based rewards which rely on human raters or a trained reward model, verifiable rewards can be checked automatically and unambiguously, making them a highly reliable and scalable source of training signal for tasks that have definite right answers.\n\n## Self-Improvement Without Ground Truth\n\nInterestingly, recent research explores self-improvement even when ground truth isn't available. One novel approach enables models to self-improve through self-judging by leveraging the generator-verifier gap, investigating whether models can provide reliable reward signals without access to ground truth answers. Researchers demonstrated that LLMs functioning as judges provide stable reward signals, establishing a complete self-improvement loop without requiring external verification by implementing a system where models generate their own practice problems, solve them, and then evaluate the correctness of their solutions.\n\n## Verifier Requirements\n\nVerifiable reward construction uses decomposed rewards designed to be reconstructible from evidence bundles, with components that score tool validity, task success using deterministic evaluators when available, and skill reuse.\n\nThe key tension in your query—the need for ground truth when no signal exists—is being addressed through self-judging approaches that leverage the asymmetry between generating and verifying solutions."],"durationSeconds":14.151079749999568,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"04adf0ca-2c7b-4b12-a7e0-51943edcd195","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
