{"parentUuid":"c263fb85-fd7b-49f4-b7c2-12ae6fad1b90","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"ac8f883e15ef792f8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016HB9JWu5erW1iJMHrDAbWX","type":"tool_result","content":"# AlphaEvolve's Evaluation Requirements\n\nHere are the relevant verbatim passages about AlphaEvolve's need for automated evaluation:\n\n**On user-supplied evaluation functions:**\n> \"AlphaEvolve requires an automatic evaluation mechanism to assess the quality of generated solutions. This is provided by a user-defined function, which takes a solution and returns a dictionary of scalar metrics to be maximized.\"\n\n**On evaluation function examples:**\n> \"For simple problems, such as finding large graphs with specific properties, this function may only check a condition and return a single score.\"\n\nThe article does not explicitly state that tasks requiring manual experimentation are out of scope. However, it emphasizes throughout that the system depends on automated evaluation mechanisms—the evaluator must be something the system can call programmatically rather than requiring human judgment for each iteration."}]},"uuid":"58905b71-142a-47f4-b282-5f9cf4085e87","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:36.678Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":169743,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# AlphaEvolve's Evaluation Requirements\n\nHere are the relevant verbatim passages about AlphaEvolve's need for automated evaluation:\n\n**On user-supplied evaluation functions:**\n> \"AlphaEvolve requires an automatic evaluation mechanism to assess the quality of generated solutions. This is provided by a user-defined function, which takes a solution and returns a dictionary of scalar metrics to be maximized.\"\n\n**On evaluation function examples:**\n> \"For simple problems, such as finding large graphs with specific properties, this function may only check a condition and return a single score.\"\n\nThe article does not explicitly state that tasks requiring manual experimentation are out of scope. However, it emphasizes throughout that the system depends on automated evaluation mechanisms—the evaluator must be something the system can call programmatically rather than requiring human judgment for each iteration.","durationMs":7098,"url":"https://artgor.medium.com/paper-review-alphaevolve-a-coding-agent-for-scientific-and-algorithmic-discovery-5732a876c2e2"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c263fb85-fd7b-49f4-b7c2-12ae6fad1b90","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"58905b71-142a-47f4-b282-5f9cf4085e87","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ac8f883e15ef792f8","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01BBjSxh6vYiz3u1yQ5cFHvt","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have strong, well-sourced material. Here are the falsifiable claims.\n\n---\n\n## Falsifiable claims: self-improving code systems require a ground-truth evaluator\n\n**1. AlphaEvolve verifies, runs, and scores every proposed program using automated evaluation metrics — the loop's accept/reject signal is the automated score.**\nURL: https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\nQuote: \"AlphaEvolve verifies, runs and scores the proposed programs using automated evaluation metrics.\"\n\n**2. AlphaEvolve can only be applied to problems whose solution is an algorithm that can be automatically verified — i.e., machine-gradeable problems.**\nURL: https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\nQuote: \"it can be applied to any problem whose solution can be described as an algorithm, and automatically verified.\" Also: \"This makes AlphaEvolve particularly helpful in a broad range of domains where progress can be clearly and systematically measured, like in math and computer science.\"\n\n**3. The requirement for an automated evaluator is explicitly named as AlphaEvolve's primary limitation — tasks needing manual experimentation are out of scope (no automated signal = the method does not apply).**\nURL: https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf (AlphaEvolve paper, surfaced via search snippet)\nQuote: \"While the use of an automated evaluation metric offers AlphaEvolve a key advantage, it is also a limitation — in particular, it puts tasks that require manual experimentation out of our scope.\"\n\n**4. AlphaEvolve's evaluation signal must be a user-defined function returning a dictionary of scalar metrics to be maximized — the human supplies the ground-truth scorer, the system optimizes against it.**\nURL: https://artgor.medium.com/paper-review-alphaevolve-a-coding-agent-for-scientific-and-algorithmic-discovery-5732a876c2e2 (paper review)\nQuote: \"AlphaEvolve requires an automatic evaluation mechanism to assess the quality of generated solutions. This is provided by a user-defined function, which takes a solution and returns a dictionary of scalar metrics to be maximized.\"\n\n**5. The Darwin Gödel Machine uses real coding benchmarks (SWE-bench, Polyglot) as the empirical fitness signal that validates whether each self-modification is actually an improvement.**\nURL: https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.22954\nQuote: \"Empirically, the DGM automatically improves its coding capabilities (e.g., better code editing tools, long-context window management, peer-review mechanisms), increasing performance on SWE-bench from 20.0% to 50.0%, and on Polyglot from 14.2% to 30.7%.\" (The benchmark score is the fitness function that selects which mutated agents enter the archive.)\n\n**6. STOP (Self-Taught Optimizer) is structured entirely around a utility function: the seed improver improves programs \"according to a given utility function,\" and self-improvement is selected by measured downstream utility gain.**\nURL: https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.02304\nQuote: \"We start with a seed 'improver' that improves an input program according to a given utility function by querying an LM several times and returning the best solution.\"\n\n**7. STOP's recursive self-improvement is an optimization problem defined over a measurable objective — the meta-utility averaging downstream task performance is what drives each iteration; without it there is no objective to optimize.**\nURL: https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2310.02304\nQuote: \"the goal is to find an improver program I that has high expected utility when used on a downstream task\" and \"returns the best solution according to the utility function\" — improvement is selected by \"a downstream utility improvement.\"\n\n**8. The general principle: verifiable rewards (objectively checkable against known ground truth) are the reliable, scalable training signal for LLM self-improvement, distinguished from preference/learned rewards precisely because they can be checked automatically and unambiguously.**\nURL: https://www.ai21.com/glossary/foundational-llm/what-are-verifiable-rewards/ (via search synthesis)\nClose paraphrase: Verifiable rewards are reward signals where output correctness \"can be confirmed objectively against a known ground truth... checked automatically and unambiguously, making them a highly reliable and scalable source of training signal for tasks that have definite right answers\" — in contrast to preference-based rewards relying on human raters or a trained reward model.\n\nNote: Claim 8's wording is from a search-result synthesis of the AI21 glossary page (not a direct WebFetch of the page), so it is the lowest-confidence item; verify the exact phrasing before quoting it as verbatim. Claims 1, 2, 5, 6 are verbatim from primary sources (DeepMind blog, arXiv abstracts). Claim 3 is verbatim from the AlphaEvolve paper but surfaced via search snippet rather than a successful PDF fetch (the PDF is binary-encoded) — strong but worth a direct confirmation against the PDF text if it will be quoted load-bearingly."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":585,"cache_read_input_tokens":23919,"output_tokens":1840,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":585},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":1840,"cache_read_input_tokens":23919,"cache_creation_input_tokens":585,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":585,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2CGox2tiavunQX5BXj","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"6be63d7f-c0cd-46b9-8069-def602631697","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:58.525Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
